com.android.build.transform.api
Interface Transform

All Known Subinterfaces:
AsInputTransform, CombinedTransform, ForkTransform, NoOpTransform
@Beta
public interface Transform

A Transform that processes build content. The Transform indicates what it applies to (content, scope) and what it generates (content, format), which is used when the transform is added to the list of tasks through the TransformManager. It receives the content as TransformInput objects, and writes the result into one or more TransformOutput. However this base interface does not actually handles inputs/outputs. This is handled by children interfaces. It can also have secondary input and output files. These are handled separately from the content objects.

Method Detail

getName

@NonNull
java.lang.String getName()
Returns the unique name of the transform. This is associated with the type of work that the transform does. It does not have to be unique per variant.

getInputTypes

@NonNull
java.util.Set<ScopedContent.ContentType> getInputTypes()
Returns the type(s) of data that is consumed by the Transform. This may be more than one type.

getOutputTypes

@NonNull
java.util.Set<ScopedContent.ContentType> getOutputTypes()
Returns the type(s) of data that is generated by the Transform. This may be more than one type.

getScopes

@NonNull
java.util.Set<ScopedContent.Scope> getScopes()
Returns the scope(s) of the Transform. This indicates what the transform consumes, not in term of content types, but in term of which streams it consumes.

getReferencedScopes

@NonNull
java.util.Set<ScopedContent.Scope> getReferencedScopes()
Returns the referenced scope(s) for the Transform. These scopes are not consumed by the Transform. They are provided as inputs, but are still available as inputs for other Transforms to consume.

getTransformType

@NonNull
Transform.Type getTransformType()
Returns the type of the Transform. This indicates how the Transform manipulate its inputs to create outputs.

getOutputFormat

@NonNull
ScopedContent.Format getOutputFormat()
Returns the format of the output stream(s) that this Transform writes into.

getSecondaryFileInputs

@NonNull
java.util.Collection<java.io.File> getSecondaryFileInputs()
Returns a list of additional file(s) that this Transform needs to run. Changes to files returned in this list will trigger a new execution of the Transform even if the streams haven't been touched. Any changes to these files will trigger a non incremental execution.

getSecondaryFileOutputs

@NonNull
java.util.Collection<java.io.File> getSecondaryFileOutputs()
Returns a list of additional (out of streams) file(s) that this Transform creates. These File instances can only represent files, not folders. For folders, use getSecondaryFolderOutputs() Changes to files returned in this list will trigger a new execution of the Transform even if the streams haven't been touched. Changes to these output files force a non incremental execution.

getSecondaryFolderOutputs

@NonNull
java.util.Collection<java.io.File> getSecondaryFolderOutputs()
Returns a list of additional (out of streams) folder(s) that this Transform creates. These File instances can only represent folders. For files, use getSecondaryFileOutputs() Changes to folders returned in this list will trigger a new execution of the Transform even if the streams haven't been touched. Changes to these output folders force a non incremental execution.

getParameterInputs

@NonNull
java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object> getParameterInputs()
Returns a map of non-file input parameters using a unique identifier as the map key. Changes to values returned in this map will trigger a new execution of the Transform even if the streams haven't been touched. Changes to these values force a non incremental execution.

isIncremental

boolean isIncremental()
Returns whether the Transform can perform incremental work. If it does, then the TransformInput will contains a list of changed/removed/added files.
